  "texts": [
    "As a result, without any intervention, the naive representation learning may regress out the signal of interest, as was the case with PCA and even the state-of-the art batch correction method, Harmony (Antonsson and Melsted, 2024) (Supplementary Figure 2).",
    "Representation learning, therefore, is rarely used for clinical genomics applications.",
    "Instead, classical regularized supervised learning methods (e.g.",
    "ElasticNet) are adopted, which are able to resolve the p (number of features) >> n (number of samples) problem by finding an adequate balance between the number of features the model utilizes and the individual weight of each feature.",
    "While these methods have been extensively applied in clinical genomics and liquid biopsy, they fail to model non-linear interactions among the input features and the higher-order patterns in the data."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}